segments.text: How could a visitor to the NM campus who was totally unaware, perhaps, of the difference between, say, a freshman, sophomore, junior, and senior, how could he tell what was what without asking somebody?
Freshman wore a fish stripe on his sleeve, but they usually were pretty easy to identify anyway.
Uh-huh.
Sophomore usually was a corporal in the Corps, had had corporal stripes.
Junior had sergeant stripes, and so forth.
At one point, I think there was a junior pin that was fairly prevalent on campus, seemingly, that the juniors could wear.
Well, they had freshman pins.
I don't know whether they had sophomore pins or not, but the freshman
I got the concession one year for selling freshman pins.
It was a little gold pin in the shape of a fish.
And it was quite profitable.
Selling the pins, I guess.
Yes.
But it was an optional thing then, not everybody wore one.
Yeah.
OK.
I think you've talked a little bit about this, but perhaps there are some other things.
What did you do for entertainment and recreation?
Well, I had no time to engage in too much entertainment and recreation, but there was
the recreation usually was in the nature of some sort of horseplay and games that you played and intramural activities and so forth.
But the truth is there was very little time for any
formal education.
The old YMCA had one or two pool tables and they weren't used very much.
I think, as I look back on it, that I was so busy with the things I had to do that I didn't have time to
look for entertainment.
But were there other students who did have more time, or was it a general rule that almost everybody worked?
No, no, no.
There were a good many that didn't work.
Most of them didn't.
I would say that they, in their off time, that they
just fool around.
Uh-huh, had a good time in the dormitory.
Okay, what about occasional dances?
Yes, we had some dances that were big occasions on the campus those days, and they were well attended.

and uh well run i don't remember ever uh seeing anybody take a drink of whiskey and that sort of thing it of course in those days if you got caught with it you were automatically expelled and they were very well uh run uh occasions and we look forward to those dances and uh
Most of us would invite our girl to come and we emptied some of the dormitories and let the girls stay in the dormitories.
And it was usually a two day occasion to enjoy.
And we had some of the best bands that were available at that time.
And I remember one time we had Ligon Smith.
There's not many people I know that are old enough to remember Ligon Smith, but it cost us $800 to get his band down there.
I remember that.
Did the Corps of Cadet officers have any special privileges not enjoyed by, say, other upperclassmen?
Well, I don't know.
They had...
a good deal of delegated authority and sometimes they felt that they didn't have enough and I'm sure they did have.
They primarily did what then?
Enforce discipline within the armatory?
Yes.
Did they assign you extra drill if you were caught misbehaving?
Or did somebody higher up have to assign that?
I don't remember.
They issued demerits.
And when you got so many demerits, you had to work them off.
And so the upperclassmen didn't actually assign the extra work, but the officers could give you demerits.
I see.
And that was for a number of things.
If your room was not...
orderly, where you got demerits, if you were late formation and things like that.
Did you have any favorite instructors or professors at A&M?
Yes, generally speaking I liked them all, but I
You mentioned Charlie Crawford a while ago.
Charlie Crawford was one of my freshman instructors, and we established a friendship that has continued till today.
He was one of the greatest friends I ever had and one of the best instructors I ever had.
And in my freshman year, I had Dr. Thomas Mayo as my English teacher.
professor and Dr. Mayo took a special interest and he organized the debating club and the literary club and I did join his literary club for
occasional book reviews and that sort of thing.

I didn't have joined the debating club because I didn't have time, but Tommy Mayo was also the head librarian, and I went to work in the library dusting off and putting up the books at $16 a month and for so many hours a day, and
I've always said that I absorbed a good deal of knowledge putting up the books in the library.
Well, I'm interested to hear your comments about Mr. Crawford because he's one of the retired professors whom I know quite well, and I find him to be an interesting and helpful sort of man.
13 years after I graduated, he persuaded me to enroll for

obtaining a professional degree, which I don't believe they still give, but it consisted of enrolling in the fall, preparing and writing a thesis, and standing examination at the graduation in the spring.
And I did that.
And I have, I think, one of the few professional degrees.
Your qualifications were a certain amount of experience before you could enroll for this degree.
But I have kept in touch with Charlie Crawford all through the years and knew his family well and admire him very much.
The other professor that I would, that I recall that I was very fond of was Mr.
Brewer.
I've forgotten his initials.
He was in the mechanical engineering department.
He first taught me lab courses, and then in my senior year in mechanical engineering, we had a group
who elected to specialize in railroad engineering.
And he was an old railroad man before he came to A&M, and he taught this class.
And although it had nothing to do with my career later on, I enjoyed this work under Mr.
Brewer.
What...
Attitudes did the students have towards the administration, say the president of A&M?
Dr. Brazell, I believe, was president.
Dr. Brazell.
Well, their attitude was both good and bad.
Dr. Brazell had some difficulty in having...
had experience as president of a girls' school and had some difficulty in getting the viewpoints of the boys.
And there was occasions when the situation got pretty rough, and the boys were not always respectful.
some of them, and there was, I guess, occasions when it looked like we were going to have a riot and he threatened to close the school down and that sort of thing.
When I first came to A&M three years ago, I had the impression that Dr. Brazell was really a top-notch man,
And then one of the other former students, and I've forgotten just exactly who it was now, but I believe it was Mr.
Height from Austin, brought me an issue of a kind of an underground student newspaper called The Lung Bat, which came out in 1924 while Dr. Brazell was still there.
And they complained about all sorts of things, Charlie Nietzsche's laundry and the confectionery.
And then they had an editorial in which they sort of said they were complaining about censorship, I believe, of the newspaper.
And they said that, well, and, you know, the inability of students being able to get up and say what they really thought.
And they said...

that if you don't believe us, why get up in the middle of the academic building and say what you think, and then see, look how long it is till the next train comes through, and that's how long you'll be here.
Well, we had some of those kind of problems.
I really was very fond of Dr. Brazell, and I remember I even visited him after we went to Oklahoma University.
He was a learned man and an educator,
but he didn't always know how to best handle a bunch of boys.
Perhaps he really hadn't had the background experience for handling a bunch of boys of that size, of that type of school.
I think that pretty well explains it.
Were there any new traditions?
Of course, you know, Mr.
Colonel Ike Ashburn was commandant in those days, and
He was one of the most effective men that I've ever known and got to be a very good friend of mine even up until he died after he left A&M.
But he was the real strength of the
administrative part of the discipline and administrative part of the student activities and did a fine job.
So would then maybe the editorial and the long bat been aimed more at the Colonel Ashburn than at Dr. Bazell?
No, I don't think so.
In those days, it was easier.
You were expelled for things that you wouldn't be expelled for today, possibly.
And hazing was the biggest reason for expelling the students.
And every time a group would get caught in the act,
and get expelled from school, that would stir the whole corps up.
And that's when these riotous situations seem to exist.
Now, what I was starting to ask is, were there any new traditions started while you were a student at A&M?
I know there's lots of things that are carried on today, such as the bonfire that started well before you were there, a number of other things.
Well, I don't recall.
It just seems to me that
The traditions were there and are still there, maybe somewhat modified as of today.
They were there.
I think one of the ones that I miss most, I did not attend A&M, but I came to the campus on a number of occasions.
I was in a debating club at Texas Lutheran when I was a student, and we came to A&M on several occasions for the debate tournament here.
And one of the things which always impressed me was the friendly greetings that you got from every student as you encountered him on the campus.
This would have been in the early 50s.
Yes.
But you don't get that today.
Well, more so than you do in other schools, but... Yeah, I think more so than in other schools, but it's, I think, unfortunately, rapidly dying out.
Well, numbers have something to do with that.
I think there was only about 2,000 students enrolled when I was there, and I believe I knew the nickname of most of them.
I had a job delivering telegrams, and...
It was all over the campus.
And in my sophomore year, I had a job at telegrams and library and mess hall.
Three jobs in one year.
I had a little excess money for the first time.
Of course, in my senior year, I had the hamburger stand.
That was the famous hamburger stand.
Yes.
Could you tell us a little bit about that hamburger stand?
Well, yes.
It was those students who could prove the need for some help were allowed to draw with others that had been selected.
And I think there must have been about 25 or 30 of us who qualified to draw for the concession.
The one who drew the concession was permitted to buy the stand from the one who had had it, not on any negotiated price, but on the same price that he paid for it.
I drew, Colonel Todd was then a commandant, and we went to his office, and I had to deal with my roommate, who also qualified to draw, that you had to have a partner.
So then I selected my partner in advance, and he selected me in advance.
See, one of us got it, we were partners.
So I drew it.
Number 25 was a lucky number, and I drew it out of the hat.

Well, I didn't have $250 to pay for it, and I wasn't old enough to borrow money at the bank, but I went over to the Brown Bank and explained my situation, and they said, well, we will loan you money if you'll get somebody to sign your note.
I went back and talked to Tommy Mayo, and Tommy said, I'll sign your note.
So he signed it, and I got the $250 and paid for the stand.
And then, incidentally, that $250 paid off before Thanksgiving that year.
But after I went to summer camp and coming back from summer camp, I stopped at college and the 4-H Club boys were there.
And so I got Dad Cole, who worked for us and was engaged to work for us in the stand.
We opened up the hamburger stand and split the
profits three ways.
We each made $50 that week, and I had enough money to buy a railroad ticket back to Dallas when it was over.
Then when we graduated and lost the concession, the athletic department took over the hamburger stand.
It always before had gone on a concession basis.
Now, that was an experience for me.
We sold hamburgers for 10 cents apiece, bought the ground meat for 10 cents a pound, and made about 4 or 5 cents profit on each hamburger.
So it was quite profitable.
What all did you put everything on the hamburger that you put on the day, like lettuce and tomatoes and onions?
No, to me, that doesn't make a hamburger.
That's a sandwich.
A hamburger...
is meat, bread, mustard, pickles, and onions.
Now, at present time, they call them hamburgers, but it's not hamburger to me when they make a sandwich with lettuce and tomatoes and stuff.
So that hamburger stand had been there for a number of years, then, I take it, before you got the concession.
It had been there two or three years.
And then you were the last one to have it before the athletic department took it?
Before the athletic department took it over, yes.
Did the people have to come to your stand to get the hamburger?
Yes.
You didn't deliver it to the dormitory?
Well, each evening when I got through and went by, and if there was meat left over, I'd stay there and cook them up in hamburgers, and I sent my agents out in the dormitories and sold them.
He gave them 15% commission.
so that I could clean up the supply of meat every day.
Then you had a number of people working for you, I take it?
Yes, I had some student help.
I paid them 25 cents an hour and all the hamburgers they could eat, which looked like a good job to them.
Okay.
Were there any girls in any of your classes when you were at A&M?
No.
They weren't...
Prior to, well, I don't know how to time it.
I remember Elaine Bazell graduated from A&M.
She was the first girl, I guess, to get a degree from A&M.
And in a period of time there, and maybe it was while we were there, the daughters of the professors could attend the classes on a day
scheduled basis, but I had no girls in my classes.
Uh-huh.
It would depend, I take it, probably on the course that you were taking, whether you...
Yes.
I would think you might have had some in a literature class or something.
Yes, maybe so.
Well, I think Mr. Crawford's sister is the one who's usually given credit as being the first graduate.
That could be.
She's now Mrs. Ludeke, I believe.
She finished in 24, but I don't believe she... She didn't participate in a formal graduation.
I think she got a degree of some sort.
Uh-huh.
But, of course, there were some earlier who attended and completed the courses but didn't get anything.
Yeah.
You mentioned something a little bit earlier about the training table.
Could you tell us a little bit about what this involved and what other privileges, say, the athletes had?
Well, the food was very...
They had steaks every evening, T-bone steaks usually, and it was quite an inducement to become a good athlete and make the training table.
The training table wasn't open to everybody who went out for athletics.
It was just available for the squad.
In other words, by the squad, you mean this would be the fellows who played football who made the trips?
Well, I don't know.
I guess the limitations changed from time to time.
But if they were active on the squad, they were on the training table.
And they had their own dining room in the Duncan Hall, Duncan Dining Room in the attached, I mean, part of Spieser Hall.
Uh-huh.
Now, if you played football, were you on the training table the whole year or just during football season?
Or, well, you could say about, you were on cross country, I believe, were you not?
Yes.
You made the training table.
Did you eat at the training table the whole year or just during the cross country season?
No, I don't believe it was for the whole year.
But they, I don't recall how it was for the rest of the athletes.
The football people, of course, they had spring practice, and they had the football season.
And really, I guess it was, for the football players, a pretty year-round thing.
Did the athletes have any other privileges?
I mean, were they ever excused from drill or?
Not, they weren't supposed to be.
And they lived, when you were there, they lived with their company.
Yes.
This one was assigned to a company and he lived with the company.
That's right.
He was in a separate dorm.
Yes.
Okay.
Were you on the cross-country team just one year or more than one?
For one year, I believe, I developed a case of sin splints.
I had to give it up.
I wasn't on in my senior year.
I was on my junior year.
OK. Well, I think that sort of covers what I want to talk to you about while you were at A&M.
Now, if time will permit, I'd like to talk with you some about what you've done since then.
What was your first job?
Well, my first job, I took a job at $100 a month working for the Continental Gin Company.
I only worked six months for them, and I went to work for the Lone Star Gas Company, also at $100 a month, but work that I felt would give me an opportunity to become an engineer.
But having taken mechanical engineering, I had no special qualifications in the petroleum field.
But through experience and I obtained a reputation or an opportunity to become a petroleum engineer, and I was the first
petroleum engineer that Lone Star Gas Company had.
And I've been a petroleum engineer ever since and never a mechanical engineer.
Did you take some additional courses somewhere while you were working for Lone Star Gas or something?
No.
Just experience?
Experience.
How long did you work for Lone Star Gas?
Thirteen years.
Then I came having, I came to Amarillo to take over the Shamrock Oil and Gas Corporation.
which was about nine years old and had accumulated a total loss of $9 million.
And I've been here ever since.
I was first vice president and general manager and then president and then chairman of the board.
What year was it that you came to Diamond, Chairman?
1938, December 1938.
Are you still chairman of the board?
I'm retired now.
I remember before my retirement, we affected a merger with the Diamond Alkali people, and the company is now known as the Diamond Shamrock Company, chemical and oil business.
They complement each other very well.
It's a rather large corporation, going to do nearly a billion dollars worth of business this year.
And I am still a member of the board of directors, but not active in the management of the company because of my retirement.
I've been retired five years from active job.
I think we're
